Crypto (Could) Fixes This
One way to think about crypto is as an insurance policy.
You pay for it, kinda hate it, pay for it, hope you never need it, pay for =
it=E2=80=A6 and then PHEW.=C2=A0
It=E2=80=99s not the sexiest sales pitch for a new technology, but this is =
a bear market after all. And over the past few months, I keep seeing things=
 that make me whisper to myself, so no one else hears=E2=80=A6 =E2=80=9CCry=
pto could fix this.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
Take Twitter.=C2=A0
Last Thursday, as we were preparing the Weekly Dose and dropping in Twitter=
 links which magically turned into Twitter embeds like we always do, we got=
 hit with this popup:=C2=A0=C2=A0
I thought it was an API issue, because I=E2=80=99m a sap who assumes the be=
st in people. Then on Friday morning, I hopped on to Twitter to discover th=
at any tweet including a link with =E2=80=9Csubstack.com=E2=80=9D in it cou=
ldn=E2=80=99t be liked or retweeted. My fellow Substackers were in shambles=
=2E I=E2=80=99d share their tweets to show=
 you, but tweet embedding is still=20=
down.=C2=A0
Elon hasn=E2=80=99t given an explanation, but you don=E2=80=99t need to be =
Enola Holmes to get to the bottom of it. On Wednesday, Substack introduced =
Notes [ https://substack.com/redirect/30451e46-0a0e-42c1-bab9-15d44e28a14b?=
j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and N=
otes looks an awful lot like Twitter.
Of course, Elon paid $44 billion to own Twitter and can do what he likes, b=
ut what he likes has certainly turned out to be a bummer for those of us wh=
o rely on the platform for our livelihoods.=C2=A0
When you have a hammer, everything looks like a nail, so imagine me saying =
this with the utmost humility and the least bravado possible, but=E2=80=A6 =
crypto could fix this.=C2=A0
This kind of situation =E2=80=93 the kind in which one person or a small gr=
oup of people can make decisions that hurt users, developers, or partners o=
n a whim =E2=80=93 is exactly the kind of situation that crypto=E2=80=99s a=
dvocates have been building to prevent.=C2=A0
Specifically, decentralized social protocols like Farcaster and Lens have b=
een doing a lot of hard, unsexy work, and building products that so far loo=
k a lot like Twitter, to ensure that future social networks can make certai=
n guarantees to its users and developer partners that no one person or smal=
l group of people could violate.=C2=A0
As Farcaster co-founder Varun Srinivasan wrote in Sufficient Decentralizati=
on for Social Networks [ https://substack.com/redirect/dcd29222-2f1d-4ca6-a=
fa8-2cbbad81203e?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m=
8ExkRNpU ], =E2=80=9CA social network achieves sufficient decentralization =
if two users can find each other and communicate, even if the rest of the n=
etwork wants to prevent it,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Ccan only be true if dev=
elopers can build many clients on the network.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
On any given day, for any given user, this is a hard value proposition to g=
rok. Twitter, Facebook, Instagram, Snap, and TikTok work just fine for the =
vast majority of users most of the time.=C2=A0
The problem with Twitter, however, from the perspective of anyone trying to=
 build anything on top of it, be it an app or an audience or a relationship=
, is that on any given day, Elon could wake up in a mood and decide to chan=
ge the rules.=C2=A0
Decentralized social is Elon Insurance.=C2=A0
Decentralized social networks can provide that insurance because they separ=
ate the protocol and the clients, let the ecosystem govern the protocol, an=
d encourage anyone to build a diverse set of clients on top of it.
The protocol =E2=80=93 the service that stores users names, keeps the socia=
l graph, lets people post to the network =E2=80=93 progressively decentrali=
zes once it=E2=80=99s good enough in order to become a stable public good o=
n top of which developers can build any number of more centralized clients.=
 Those clients =E2=80=93 the equivalent of the Twitter app, the part of the=
 product that users interact with, that manages feeds, algorithms, interfac=
es, moderation, and more =E2=80=93 can be as opinionated as they=E2=80=99d =
like to be, and anyone is free to build one however they=E2=80=99d like.=C2=
=A0
Take the Substack situation, the Orange Wedding.=C2=A0
On decentralized social, the protocol would store all of the user names, ha=
ndle the relationships among users, and let people send tweets (with links,=
 images, and more) would be set practically in stone and really hard to cha=
nge, like a public good or Hyperstructure [ https://substack.com/redirect/8=
2cb7950-b355-4717-999d-a8e32efe7486?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNua=
MZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. All of the innovation would take place at th=
e client level.=C2=A0=C2=A0
There might be one client on which all Substack links and mentions are bloc=
ked and another that only shows tweets that include Substack links and ment=
ions, both pulling from the same protocol.=C2=A0
In Back to the Future of Twitter [ https://substack.com/redirect/2100a3f2-5=
cdc-4573-839f-c46b36bed40c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Ben Thompson proposed something similar, breaking Twi=
tter into two companies: TwitterAppCo (client) and TwitterServiceCo (protoc=
ol).=C2=A0
But even that architecture runs into the Elon Problem. As Thompson wrote (e=
mphasis mine), =E2=80=9CA truly open TwitterServiceCo has the potential to =
be a new protocol for the Internet =E2=80=94 the notifications and identity=
 protocol; unlike every other protocol, though, this one would be owned by =
a private company. That would be insanely valuable.=E2=80=9D =C2=A0
=E2=80=9CThis one would be owned by a private company=E2=80=9D puts us righ=
t back in the same spot. If Elon were in charge of the protocol, as Thompso=
n proposed, he could feasibly scrub substack links and tags from the databa=
se.=C2=A0
A sufficiently decentralized protocol, on the other hand, would need the ma=
jority of its token holders to wake up feeling petty in order to do the sam=
e thing, or even more if big changes required some sort of supermajority. S=
canning Twitter over the weekend, it doesn=E2=80=99t seem like a majority w=
ould back that kind of decision.=C2=A0
Crypto could fix Twitter, or at least prevent it from happening at the next=
 generation of social products. It=E2=80=99s one of those applications of t=
he technology that only becomes apparent when things break. I=E2=80=99ve se=
en a bunch of those recently.=C2=A0
When I saw the Taylor Swift / Ticketmaster debacle [ https://substack.com/r=
edirect/77af536b-afe9-49a7-bee6-51d54fc0ac91?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7=
GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], the one where scalpers and bots got=
 most of the tickets she wanted to sell to her real fans, I thought, =E2=80=
=9CCrypto could fix this.=E2=80=9D Specifically, NFTs seem like they could =
be useful insurance against scalpers by letting fans prove their fandom thr=
ough Music NFTs owned, POAPs from concerts attended, official fan club NFTs=
 and more. Ticketmaster actually seems to kind of agree. They recently roll=
ed out an NFT-gated ticket sales [ https://substack.com/redirect/eadfc12f-3=
671-4911-a335-7b731e7f873c?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] experiment with Avenged Sevenfold.=C2=A0
When SVB collapsed, leaving companies without access to their funds over a =
harrowing March weekend, I thought, =E2=80=9CCrypto could fix this.=E2=80=
=9D Specifically, the ability to self-custody at least a portion of funds t=
he same way people once kept cash under their mattress seems like decent in=
surance against bank runs. I=E2=80=99m not rooting for a collapse of the ba=
nks or expecting BTC to hit $1 million any time soon, but =E2=80=9CPeople s=
hould be able to access and use their money whenever they like=E2=80=9D doe=
sn=E2=80=99t seem like a crazy proposition.=C2=A0
And if AI really is as powerful a technology as it seems like it=E2=80=99s =
going to be, I think crypto could be a very useful insurance policy against=
 unprecedented centralization of power =E2=80=93 imagine if Elon ran OpenAI=
 instead of Sam Altman =E2=80=93 and against the verification challenges to=
 come. As Joe Weisenthal wrote, =E2=80=9CA Solution to Twitter=E2=80=99s Bo=
t Problem is Staring at Us Right in the Eyes [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/e3072ba2-38d0-416a-9c58-7c73e78ebaf8?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_Zl=
NuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].=E2=80=9D Specifically, zero-knowledge pro=
ofs [ https://substack.com/redirect/f0204258-1c2c-4bc9-abee-8742c649ac93?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] will be=
 a valuable counterpart to AI, to say nothing of the governance and ownersh=
ip mechanisms that have been cooked up in crypto=E2=80=99s laboratories [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/cd0f36ec-fc7c-405f-a3f1-a1403b6f761c?j=3DeyJ1I=
joiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] over the past f=
ew years. Plus, I really don=E2=80=99t think people will want to have their=
 wife deleted by some Trust & Safety PM at Microsoft [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/f7b0afd0-183f-427f-8db4-e341b45e17b6?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. I suspect that the free market wi=
th crypto tools will do a better job of figuring out positive sum solutions=
 to the challenges presented by AI than the government or any six month pau=
se will.=C2=A0=C2=A0
Obviously, crypto is not popular right now. It=E2=80=99s a non-starter in m=
any conversations. There=E2=80=99s a lot of work to be done to improve both=
 the image and the infrastructure, so that entrepreneurs and CFOs are able =
to use the technology in some of the ways we=E2=80=99ve discussed today wit=
hout raising eyebrows on their boards and among their users.=C2=A0
Put another way, if you told people not, =E2=80=9CYou should use crypto=E2=
=80=9D but, =E2=80=9CI have this brand new technology called Zoop or whatev=
er and here=E2=80=99s what it does,=E2=80=9D and then listed crypto=E2=80=
=99s feature set, they would say, =E2=80=9CWow, that=E2=80=99s actually sup=
er useful and exactly what I=E2=80=99m looking for=E2=80=9D and adopt the t=
echnology. We shouldn=E2=80=99t throw the benefits out with the bathwater.
Look, if you view 2023 as some sort of End of Tech and Business History, no=
thing I=E2=80=99ve written here will be particularly compelling. Twitter=E2=
=80=99s network effects are really strong. The banking industry is the bank=
ing industry. Many have tried to take down Ticketmaster before, and just as=
 many have failed. And if anyone=E2=80=99s going to control the most powerf=
ul technology ever, Sam Altman seems like as good a person as any.=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99ve read Not Boring for a while, though, you know that=E2=80=
=99s not how I view 2023. I think we=E2=80=99re still at the starting line,=
 that the technology that awes us today will look laughably primitive when =
Dev and Maya are my age, and their kids will make fun of them for the dinos=
aur tech they used. There will be new social networks, monopolies will fall=
, banks will continue to fail, and AI will only get smarter and more useful=
=2E=20
In that view of the world, it=E2=80=99s worth the short-term headache and e=
xpense to build systems that are robust and fair over the long-term.
I remain excited about all of the fun use cases of crypto =E2=80=94 the ups=
ide stuff =E2=80=94  and think that crypto=E2=80=99s ability to turbocharge=
 network effects (with the right design) will only get more important as ab=
undance accelerates and other sources of power fade. But I=E2=80=99m also c=
oming to realize that the downside protection is equally valuable. The most=
 important applications might be the ones we don=E2=80=99t want to have to =
use.=C2=A0
The world is full of people who would act like Elon if given the chance, an=
d the way things are today, those people are often given the chance. Crypto=
 could fix this.
Thanks to Dan [ https://substack.com/redirect/00c05f18-391c-4b86-8057-65a60=
9f7bae9?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU =
] for editing!
That=E2=80=99s all for today. If you enjoyed today=E2=80=99s essay, share i=
t with a friend or two. =E2=80=9Cnotboring.co=E2=80=9D links still work on =
Twitter, just don=E2=80=99t say =E2=80=9CSubstack=E2=80=9D! We=E2=80=99ll b=
e back in your inbox on Friday with another Weekly Dose of Optimism.
Thanks for reading,
Packy

